'''Oi Shrine''' (大井神社, '''Oi Jinja''') is a [[Shinto shrine]] in {{ill|Saga, Kyoto|ja|嵯峨}}, [[Ukyo-ku]], [[Kyoto]], Japan. It is one of the candidate sites for the ''[[Engishiki]]'' {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社}} “Oi Shrine”; under the modern shrine-ranking system it was classified as a {{ill|Mura-sha|ja|村社}}. The precinct stands at the north end of the famous {{ill|Togetsukyo|ja|渡月橋}} bridge and is also known as “Seki Shrine” or “Ōhashi Shrine”.{{sfn|大井神社（平凡社）|1979年}}

== Enshrined kami ==
* [[Uka-no-Mitama]] (Uga-no-Mitama-no-Kami)

Older sources say the original deities were {{ill|O-ayatsuhiko no Kami|ja|大綾津日神}}, {{ill|Ō-naobi no Kami|ja|大直日神}}, and {{ill|Kamunaobi no Kami|ja|神直日神}}.

== History ==
=== Overview ===
The foundation date is unknown. One theory links the shrine to the {{ill|Hata clan|ja|秦氏}}, who are said to have built the Katsuno Ōi Weir and enshrined a water-management deity here, but this remains unconfirmed.{{sfn|大井神社（平凡社）|1979年}} Another suggestion equates the “Yamashiro Ōi no Kami” (山代大堰神) mentioned in the ''[[Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku]]'' entry for 21 July 876 with this shrine, though that identification is also uncertain.{{sfn|大井神社（平凡社）|1979年}}

The ''[[Engishiki Jinmyōchō]]'' (927) lists an Oi Shrine in Otokuni District, [[Yamashiro Province]]. Because the present site lay in the former Katsuno District, the ''Shikinaisha Investigation Report'' argues that this shrine was actually the “Seki no Kami,” an auxiliary of [[Matsuo Taisha]], and that the true Engishiki Oi Shrine has disappeared.<ref>Kasai Yoruhito, “Oi Shrine,” in ''Shikinaisha Investigation Report, vol.&nbsp;1'', Shikinaisha Kenkyūkai (ed.), Kōgakkan Univ. Press, 1979.</ref>

On 26 March 1877 (Meiji 10) the shrine received the rank of {{ill|Mura-sha|ja|村社}} under State Shinto.<ref name="説明板"/> The present worship hall is the former honden of [[Nonomiya Shrine]], moved here.<ref name="説明板">On-site explanatory plaque.</ref>

=== Court rank ===
* 21 July 876 (Seikan 18): Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade (recorded as “Yamashiro Ōi no Kami” in the ''Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku''); identification remains uncertain.

